title: Back to the Future
description: I've heard it said that nearly every line in Back to the Future serves to move the plot forward. I haven't rated this film so highly due to scriptwriting efficiencey, but I think it clearly explains why this film is so brilliant. I have seen this film more times through than perhaps any other, and it remains to this day endlessley entertaining. So many things about this film is perfect. The pacing, characters, and general plot concept are a masterclass. The two major plots are balanced perfectly. Doc is perhaps one of the most entertaining characters ever. I love this movie.

title: Once Were Warriors
description: I was incredibly priveliged to watch this film for the first time by watching a 35mm print, that, since the film had released, had been in the possesion of Lee Tamahori himself - a personal print given to him on the film's completion. Allegedly it had never been played. Lee kindly also offered some time for Q&A. I could not have asked for a better way to experience this film for the first time. The MC for the event said prior to the film that this movie "knocked me on my ass and smacked me in the face", and I could not agree more. Tamahori's legendary film is a horrific showcase of domestic violence, alcoholism, and despicable acts that drive people to unspeakable lengths. Astoundingly sobering, and rocked me to my core. It deserves all the praise it gets, and then some. I consider this film esssential watching for life.

title: The Bridge on the River Kwai

description: Katabuchi's telling of the life of a girl in Kure, Japan, during the course of World War II is an ambitious grand achievement in animated cinema. It's extended version is the longest animated film ever made. Suzu's story is told in a way that balances her life in general, but ultimatley how WWII comes to dominate it as the film draws on. Events are depicted in fantastic historical detail, with dates for reference, which I applaud. This film is sweet, heartwarming, brutal and sad in parts. A true epic.

title: A Brighter Summer Day
description: This film affected me for days aftewards, and this is perhaps not directly unrelated to it's astounding length - just shy of four hours. Yang's film is a true epic of life in a martial law Taiwan, with constant reminders of Japanese colonial past, and American influenced present intertwining into the core story of this film. The final act of this film flies in the face of the four hours preceeding it and makes one question what the point of it all was. I'm not sure if I can answer that, but what I do know is that I went on a journey that left me seriously questioning people's actions, and a much gained understanding of that period in history.

But most memorable about this film is the character of Cameron. Cameron, as some have theorized is who the film is really about, is deeply troubled. Through the actions of Ferris, Cameron comes to challenge these demons in an epic moment of finally choosing ones' self.

description: Possibly the most arresting film in this list, Love & Pop is one of the very few examples of Hideaki Anno's non-anime film output. Shot entirely on handy-cams, we see an incredibly convincing presentation of compensated dating, in order to satisfy essentially consumerist desires. Features some of the most bizzare camera angles in film, and a handul of moments that are... shocking.

description: Sister Act is a movie I love because it intersects with so many areas of interest in my life. I enojy Soul music, anything with a choir in it, and I have for several years now been fascinated with Christianity, particularly the branch closest to me, the Catholic church. This movie bundles all of that together - and it's amazing. You probably need to have at least a basic understanding of the Catholic church for many of the jokes to hit, but if you like lame Christian jokes like I do this movie is a hit. On top of that, you get a heartfelt exploration of a clash of cultures, with epic gospel numbers interspersed. I don't recall smiling as much as I did in the last 10 minutes of this movie for a long time.
